              "text": "The fundamental difference between civil law and common law systems lies in their primary source of law and the resulting judicial methodology. Civil law systems, rooted in the Roman tradition, are characterized by legal positivism, where codified statutes and comprehensive legislative enactments serve as the authoritative basis for law, leaving the judge to act as an investigator who applies the written code to the facts of a case. In contrast, common law systems rely on the principle of *stare decisis*, where judicial precedent and the rulings of higher courts carry the force of law. While civil law judges are generally not bound by prior decisions and focus on the internal logic of the code, common law judges perform an adversarial role, interpreting statutes through the lens of established case law to ensure consistency and incremental legal development.",
